english:
  title: Record of the Yongnam Pavilion
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The magistrate of Milyang, Kang Suk-gyeong, has restored the Yongnam Pavilion and sent me a letter saying: "The pavilion stands as the jewel of our district, yet it was cramped and tilted, unworthy of its name. I have now renewed it with three bays, reinforced with supporting beams and painted with vermillion and gold—neither extravagant nor shabby. My elder brother once promised to write its record but did not complete it. Knowing that no one understands him as you do, I humbly ask that you write it for me."

    Alas, can one write a record while sitting at a distance?

    Kang is the younger brother of Kang Kwan, Minister of State and holder of the title "Civil and Martial Duke." When the throne appointed him as prime minister, it grieved the sovereign that his mother remained in Jinju, too aged to come to court. Learning that Milyang lay close to Jinju, the throne appointed Kang magistrate there, that he might serve his mother. Moreover, he was granted leave to visit his mother once each year.

    In the year kyeongsin, upon returning from such a visit, the minister spoke to me, saying: "My younger brother governs Milyang with such grace that his people love him though he offers no special favors, and they fear him though he employs no harshness. All matters are attended to, the neglected restored. He has renewed the old pavilion into something of magnificent openness and clarity, incomparable in beauty. He has undertaken great works without troubling his people, all accomplished with ease. His talents as an administrator surpass even my own. I rejoice in his abilities and have promised to write his record. The draft is complete." We examined it together. Soon after, the minister fell ill and never recovered. I asked his son about the draft, but he knew nothing of it. Oh, what a loss!

    Now receiving the magistrate's letter, I find it difficult not merely to write from afar, but to do so at all—how could I bear it? Yet I cannot bear to leave the minister's wish unfulfilled. I have followed this minister for decades and have never seen him speak lightly in praise or blame of another, much less of his own brother. Kang's abilities are surely worthy of trust.

    That his people love him without special favor shows his benevolence runs deep. That they fear him without harshness shows his authority commands respect. That all flourishes and the neglected is restored shows his governance is swift and keen. When benevolence and authority shine forth together, guided by such keen administration, their reach extends far beyond a single pavilion or a single district.

    Moreover, the southern regions were once the domain of Silla, and across sixty-odd counties great and small, none lack their pavilions and pleasure grounds. Yet their names are drawn merely from what the eye beholds. This pavilion alone bears the name "Yongnam"—and thus without ascending its heights, one may perceive from afar that its rivers and mountains possess the finest beauty of all the south.

    What difficulty, then, in writing from a distance? The pavilion's former fame rested upon the natural splendor of its landscape. Yet now its newly opened grandeur allows the rivers and mountains to share their beauty with human artistry. This too is worthy of record.
  footnotes:
    - Kang Kwan (1417-1464) was a renowned statesman and scholar, also known as 'Mungyeong-gong' (文景公). He served as Prime Minister under King Sejo.
    - Kyeongsin year refers to 1460 in the lunar calendar.
    - The "three bays" (三楹) refers to the structural configuration of the pavilion with three sections.
    - Silla refers to the ancient Korean kingdom that once ruled the southern regions.
